proof.p:
The row-column rule for matrix-vector multiplication says that if A has rows r_1,r_2,\ldots,r_m and x is a vector, then
Ax = \mat[c]{ \matrow{r_1};
\matrow{r_2};
\vdots ;
\matrow{r_m}}
x
= \vec{r_1x r_2x \vdots, r_mx}.

The  of matrix multiplication is
A\mat{| | ,, |; c_1 c_2 \cdots, c_p; | | ,, |} =
\mat{| | ,, |; Ac_1 Ac_2 \cdots, Ac_p; | | ,, |}.
It follows that

  \mat[c]{ \matrow{r_1};
  \matrow{r_2};
  \vdots ;
  \matrow{r_m}}
  \mat{| | ,, |; c_1 c_2 \cdots, c_p; | | ,, |}
  = \mat{ r_1c_1 r_1c_2 \cdots, r_1c_p;
  r_2c_1 r_2c_2 \cdots, r_2c_p;
  \vdots, \vdots, , \vdots;
  r_mc_1 r_mc_2 \cdots, r_mc_p}.

example.p:
          The row-column rule allows us to compute the product matrix one entry at a time:

            \def\g{\textcolor{green!70!black}}
            \def\b{\textcolor{blue!50}}
            \begin{aligned}
            \mat{\g1 \g2 \g3; 4 5 6}
            \mat{\b1 -3; \b2 -2; \b3 -1}
            \amp= \mat{\g1\cdot\b1+\g2\cdot\b2+\g3\cdot\b3 \fbox{\phantom 8};
            \fbox{\phantom 8} \fbox{\phantom 8}}
            = \mat{\textcolor{purple}{14} \fbox{\phantom 8}; \fbox{\phantom 8} \fbox{\phantom 8}} \\
            \mat{1 2 3; \g4 \g5 \g6}
            \mat{\b1 -3; \b2 -2; \b3 -1}
            \amp= \mat{\fbox{\phantom 8} \fbox{\phantom 8};
            \g4\cdot\b1+\g5\cdot\b2+\g6\cdot\b3 \fbox{\phantom 8}}
            = \mat{14 \fbox{\phantom 8}; \textcolor{purple}{32} \fbox{\phantom 8}}
            \end{aligned}

	You should try to fill in the other two boxes!

ul.li:
Matrix multiplication does not satisfy the cancellation law: AB=AC does not imply B=C, even when A\neq 0.  For example,
\mat{1 0; 0 0}\mat{1 2; 3 4} = \mat{1 2; 0 0}
= \mat{1 0; 0 0}\mat{1 2; 5 6}.

proof.p:
First we verify that T\circ U is linear. Let u,v be vectors in \R^p. Then
\begin{split} T\circ U(u+v) \amp= T(U(u+v)) = T(U(u)+U(v)) \\ \amp= T(U(u))+T(U(v)) = T\circ U(u) + T\circ U(v). \end{split}
If c is a scalar, then T\circ U(cv) = T(U(cv)) = T(cU(v)) = cT(U(v)) = cT\circ U(v). Since T\circ U satisfies the two defining properties, it is a linear transformation.

example.p:
In this , we showed that the standard matrix for the counterclockwise rotation of the plane by an angle of \theta is
A = \mat{\cos\theta, -\sin\theta; \sin\theta, \cos\theta}.
Let T\colon\R^2\to\R^2 be counterclockwise rotation by 45^\circ, and let U\colon\R^2\to\R^2 be counterclockwise rotation by 90^\circ.  The matrices A and B for T and U are, respectively,


    A \amp= \mat{\cos(45^\circ) -\sin(45^\circ); \sin(45^\circ) \cos(45^\circ)}
    = \frac 1{\sqrt 2}\mat{1 -1; 1 1}


    B \amp= \mat{\cos(90^\circ) -\sin(90^\circ); \sin(90^\circ) \cos(90^\circ)}
    = \mat{0 -1; 1 0}.


Here we used the trigonometric identities


    \cos(45^\circ) \amp= \frac 1{\sqrt2} \amp
    \sin(45^\circ) \amp= \frac 1{\sqrt2}


    \cos(90^\circ) \amp= 0 \amp
    \sin(90^\circ) \amp= 1.


The standard matrix of the composition T\circ U is
AB = \frac 1{\sqrt 2}\mat{1 -1; 1 1}\mat{0 -1; 1 0}
= \frac 1{\sqrt 2}\mat{-1 -1; 1 -1}.

This is consistent with the fact that T\circ U is counterclockwise rotation by 90^\circ + 45^\circ = 135^\circ:  we have
\mat{\cos(135^\circ) -\sin(135^\circ); \sin(135^\circ) \cos(135^\circ)}
= \frac 1{\sqrt 2}\mat{-1 -1; 1 -1}
because \cos(135^\circ) = -1/\sqrt2 and \sin(135^\circ) = 1/\sqrt2.

        Let us compute the matrix B for U.

